"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多舞蹈评论</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big-five-oh-69dc2f93?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Pilobolus 评论：舞蹈剧团的“大五哦！”</a> <span class="date">2023 年 7 月 20 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">纽约市芭蕾舞团评论：巴兰钦及其他芭蕾舞团</a><span class="date">2023 年 5 月 9 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/martha-graham-dance-company-in-its-founders-shadow-781038c7?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">玛莎·格雷厄姆舞蹈团：在创始人的阴影下</a><span class="date">2023 年 4 月 26 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/agua-review-pina-bauschs-brazilian-dance-spectacle-5e020dee?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“Água”评论：皮娜·鲍什 (Pina Bausch) 的巴西舞蹈奇观</a><span class="date">2023 年 3 月 7 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>作为蒂塔的姐妹，罗莎拉似乎大多心不在焉，而格特鲁迪斯仍然是一个活跃的叛逆者。她在第一幕中登场，在吃了蒂塔准备的带有春药效果的玫瑰花瓣酱鹌鹑之后，火红头发的自由灵魂在淫荡的灵魂的支持和配合下，带领着一段漫长的探戈舞曲，最后变成了脱衣舞。从她的桌子底下出现，桌子变成了滑稽的舞台。</p><p> Episodes involving all these characters and others introduced along the way, including those from the next generation of the families and revolutionary soldiers, keep the action lively but not readily comprehensible.节日让格特鲁迪斯和她的革命情人胡安·亚历杭德烈斯更加引人注目。</p>但就像鹌鹑的场景一样，这一幕让人感觉紧张。<p></p><p> “Like Water for Chocolate” concludes with a pas de deux accompanied by a Talbot aria—sung soaringly in the pit by Maria Brea —that is based on lines from “Sunstone,” a poem by Octavio Paz. The choreography, for Pedro, now in tights, and Tita, now in a translucent night dress, features couplings and lifts that feel ecstatic here and ungainly there, until a coup-de-theatre moment when, amid projections of bursting flames, the entwined情侣升入苍蝇中（ZFX 的飞行效果）。</p><p>我抓住了计划运行的四名主要演员中的三名，并且都被证明是有能力的。 Standouts included Cassandra Trenary&#39;s fleet Tita, Daniel Camargo&#39;s earthy Pedro, Chloe Misseldine&#39;s riveting Rosaura, Catherine Hurlin&#39;s quicksilver Gertrudis and, in equal measure, Carlos Gonzales&#39;s and Michael de la Nuez&#39;s blazing Juan Alejandrez.</p><p>每次演出时，我周围的观众都会随着芭蕾舞剧的火热结束而热烈欢呼。类似的反应可能会一直发生，如果奇异的、出色的舞蹈机会提供了分散注意力的注意力，让人们不再困惑于叙事。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。格雷斯科维奇为《华尔街日报》撰写有关舞蹈的文章。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 28 Jun 2023 22:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/like-water-for-chocolate-review-an-overstuffed-ballet-5c74e2e5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/like-water-for-chocolate-review-an-overstuffed-ballet-5c74e2e5<category>艺术评论</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>舞蹈/芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电影</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hispanic Society Museum & Library’s Quiet Restoration]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>该机构自 2017 年关闭以来，在计划扩建之前进行了一系列微妙的改进和修复后重新开放<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589652850350819432"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791509?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西班牙裔协会博物馆和图书馆</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nicholas Venezia/Selldorf Architects </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10098652755748144108404589652850350819432"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">迈克尔·J·刘易斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 5 月 31 日下午 5:10 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在痛苦的美西战争仅仅六年后，一个普通公民就可以创建一个向世界宣扬西班牙文化荣耀的机构<strong>，这是美国民族和解能力的非凡</strong>证明。 The Hispanic Society was founded in 1904 by Archer M. Huntington, whose family&#39;s railroad fortune gave him free rein to indulge his love of Spanish art and literature.他相信公众应该有机会参观他的私人收藏，因此他在纽约当时时尚的华盛顿高地的 155 街和百老汇街找到了一个地点。他在那里建造了一流的博物馆和图书馆，这是纽约文艺复兴时期建筑的胜利之一。</p><p>西班牙裔协会现在正期待着自己的复兴。 It reopened in May having been closed since 2017. It will soon undertake a major expansion, planned by Selldorf Architects, working in collaboration with Beyer Blinder Belle and landscape architects Reed Hilderbrand.但现在它出乎意料地提前开始了，建筑师戏称这是一次“意外修复”。</p><p>西班牙协会所在的庞大建筑群本身就有些偶然。亨廷顿把他的博物馆和图书馆建在露台上，作为一个独立的物体，就像公园里的珠宝盒一样。 But no sooner had he completed his museum than he was coaxing other institutions, on several of whose boards he sat, to join him.他会给他们建筑工地，条件是他们必须在五年内按照他批准的计划建造。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791510?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Inside the Hispanic Society</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿方索·洛萨诺/西班牙裔协会</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>前两座建于 1909 年，西边是钱币学会，北边是台地对面的美国地理学会。美洲印第安人博物馆紧随其后，于 1916 年建成，位于东边的西班牙协会旁边。 The last to build was the American Academy of Arts and Letters, added to the far west of the terrace in 1921. It is perhaps the largest collection of learned societies ever to be shoehorned onto a city block.</p><p> All of these buildings, except for the American Academy, were designed by Charles P. Huntington, Archer&#39;s cousin. (He also designed Our Lady of Esperanza, built to give the complex a Catholic church in which Spanish was spoken.) They have an exquisite visual unity that comes from their construction in Indiana limestone, their continuous cornice height and the repetition of the colossal Ionic命令。 Arrayed on a monumental axis over 500 feet in length, they represent the urbanism of the City Beautiful at its best.</p><p> Or rather would have, if the axis actually led somewhere. By the time Huntington realized he was building a cultural acropolis, developers had taken the parcel at the west end of his site.他的正式服装并没有雄伟地指向哈德逊河和远处的帕利塞德河，而是指向 11 层的里维埃拉公寓，英雄轴线在其不可爱的砖屁股上消失了。</p><p> Beginning in the 1980s, most of the cultural institutions pulled up stakes and moved elsewhere. But this presented the Society with an opportunity. It could now expand eastward into the former Museum of the American Indian (whose collections had been transferred to the Smithsonian). Here it will be able to display more of its permanent collection, the bulk of which is in storage, but also have room for temporary exhibitions. In preparation for that campaign, and to announce that the Society was about to awaken from its slumbers, it decided to improve access to its Sorolla Gallery, the room that Huntington added in 1914 to house the “Vision of Spain,” Joaquín Sorolla y Bastida&#39;s 14-painting cycle celebrating the geography and life of that country. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">&#39;Vision of Spain&#39; (1911-1919)</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap">二十世纪初西班牙杰出艺术家华金·索罗拉·巴斯蒂达 (Joaquin Sorolla y Bastida) 为庆祝祖国而创作的 14 幅纪念画作精选。 </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791979/">左：“纳瓦拉”，1914 年； Right: &#39;Aragón&#39;, 1914 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791980/"> &#39;Cataluña&#39;, 1915 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791981/"> &#39;Ayamonte&#39;, 1919 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791982/"> Detail of &#39;Castilla&#39;, 1913 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791983/"> Detail of &#39;Castilla&#39;, 1913 <span class="imageCredit">Courtesy of The Hispanic Society of America</span> </p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791984/">左：“巴伦西亚”，1916 年；右：《塞维利亚，舞蹈》，1914 年<span class="imageCredit">，由美国西班牙裔协会提供</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791985/"> Left: &#39;Sevilla, The Bullfighters&#39;, 1915;右：“卡斯蒂利亚”细节，1913 年<span class="imageCredit">由美国西班牙裔协会提供</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791986/">安装视图<span class="imageCredit">由美国西班牙裔协会提供</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791987/">安装视图<span class="imageCredit">由美国西班牙裔协会提供</span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-791988/">安装视图<span class="imageCredit">由美国西班牙裔协会提供</span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p>最新的项目规模不大，只不过是为多层露台增加了应急照明、新标牌和 ADA 残疾人电梯。但即便如此，出价仍低于大约 1000 万美元的预算——这几乎从未发生过。惊讶的建筑师意识到他们可以恢复原来的建筑和中心的有顶庭院。在外观的正式尊严之后，这个空间带来了惊喜。 A kind of Spanish cloister, it consists of an open central space surrounded by an arcaded walkway of deep-red terra cotta, Renaissance in style and richly ornamented.</p><p>但它年久失修，赤土陶器和红色美世瓷砖地板都严重破损和缺失。 All were given a deep cleaning, the missing elements patched, a new system of flexible lighting installed, and the plaster walls rendered in neutral gray (the kindest background against which to hang paintings).遗憾的是，建筑师没有重新创建原来的天窗。很久以前，当建筑物换上新的铜屋顶​​时，它就被拆除了。相反，他们计划在空间上方的照明灯上方安装电灯，以暗示日光。否则，这是最好的修复方式，几乎是看不见的。</p><p>但西班牙裔协会面临的真正挑战从来不是技术上的，而是心理上的。随着时间的推移，它看起来像是一个私人俱乐部，而不是一个公共机构。经过第一阶段的修复工作，现在已经铺开了红地毯。人们希望其多米尼加人居多的社区以及整个纽约人能够接受亨廷顿古怪而勇敢的机构的邀请，该机构旨在纪念世界上的西班牙语和葡萄牙语文化。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。刘易斯在威廉姆斯教授建筑史，并为《华尔街日报》撰写建筑评论。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 31 May 2023 21:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-modest-upgrade-for-a-grand-building-73e07ad5<category>艺术评论</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>建筑学</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[New York City Ballet Review: Balanchine and Beyond]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位传奇编舞家的作品占据了公司春季前半段的主导地位；第二个舞蹈以不同创意的新舞蹈为特色，其中包括驻场编舞贾斯汀·佩克 (Justin Peck) 创作的充满活力的作品。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10372491985353614154404589608413218308276"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-777533?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">米拉·纳东 (Mira Nadon) 和艾米莉·格里蒂 (Emilie Gerrity) 在《室内音乐 No. 2》中</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：艾琳·巴亚诺</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10372491985353614154404589608413218308276"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">罗伯特·格雷斯科维奇</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 5 月 9 日下午 5:35 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>纽约</em></p><p>纽约城市芭蕾舞团的年度春季联欢晚会于 5 月 4 日举行，大约是该团当前为期六周的演出季的中期。 For the occasion, two world premieres preceded a performance of resident choreographer and artistic adviser Justin Peck&#39;s winning “The Times Are Racing” (2017). In remarks from the stage during the gala, individual speakers trumpeted the troupe&#39;s yearlong celebration of its 75th anniversary that will start this fall. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Dance Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big-five-oh-69dc2f93?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Pilobolus 评论：舞蹈剧团的“大五哦！”</a> <span class="date">2023年7月20日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/like-water-for-chocolate-review-an-overstuffed-ballet-5c74e2e5?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“就像巧克力的水”评论：一部臃肿的芭蕾舞剧</a><span class="date">2023 年 6 月 28 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/martha-graham-dance-company-in-its-founders-shadow-781038c7?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">玛莎·格雷厄姆舞蹈团：在创始人的阴影下</a><span class="date">2023 年 4 月 26 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/agua-review-pina-bauschs-brazilian-dance-spectacle-5e020dee?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“Água”评论：皮娜·鲍什 (Pina Bausch) 的巴西舞蹈奇观</a><span class="date">2023 年 3 月 7 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>NYCB 联合创始人、著名的乔治·巴兰钦（George Balanchine，1904-1983 年）创作的芭蕾舞剧占据了春跑上半场的主导地位。这些经过时间考验的作品，有的表现出色，有的却缺乏影响力。在巴兰钦获得专业荣誉的演出中，印第安纳·伍德沃德 (Indiana Woodward) 和约瑟夫·戈登 (Joseph Gordon) 在《源泉》(La Source) (1968) 中抒情而辛辣的领衔表演，其中仙女般的女性体现了迷人的莱奥·德利伯 (Léo Delibes) 配乐中所唤起的流泉精神。但艾丽卡·佩雷拉 (Erica Pereira) 在巴兰钦 (Balanchine) 为阿尔坎杰洛·科雷利 (Arcangelo Corelli) 和安东尼奥·维瓦尔第 (Antonio Vivaldi) 创作的《广场舞》(Square Dance) (1957) 中饰演芭蕾舞演员，表现平平。同样，伊莎贝拉·拉弗雷尼埃 (Isabella LaFreniere) 在巴兰钦 (Balanchine) 的《雷蒙达变奏曲》(Raymonda Variations) 中饰演芭蕾舞演员，显得更加内敛而不是权威，这是巴兰钦 1961 年为亚历山大·格拉祖诺夫 (Alexander Glazunov) 表演的俏皮的独舞和双人舞。</p><p>巴兰钦的多部芭蕾舞剧在经历了多次停顿后，将于周年纪念日回归。本季，自 2019 年以来未曾出现过的《室内音乐 No. 2》（自 1978 年起，由 Paul Hindemith 创作）以强劲的舞台表演回归，以米拉·纳登 (Mira Nadon) 、亚伦·桑斯 (Aarón Sanz) 和埃米莉·格里蒂 (Emilie Gerrity) 以及彼得·沃克 (Peter Walker) 的演员阵容为重点，以赌博和飞镖为重点。我抓住。这部芭蕾舞剧以全男性芭蕾舞团为特色，这对于巴兰钦来说是不寻常的，事实证明，这部芭蕾舞剧充满活力，其尖锐的攻击灵感来自有时敲击的音乐。</p><p>今年秋天，当他成为公司的常驻艺术家时，NYCB 的舞者们将定期得到他的指导和艺术指导，充满希望地，该剧团为阿列克谢·拉特曼斯基 (Alexei Ratmansky) 2010 年的《纳穆纳，一场盛大的娱乐》（献给爱德华·拉洛 (Édouard Lalo)）进行了充满活力的表演。 .他的 58 分钟组曲由七位杰出舞者以及由 16 名女性和 8 名男性组成的充满活力的团体组成，在本季演出中从头到尾都令人惊叹不已，其中各演员的表演尤其令人难忘。尤尼蒂·费兰 (Unity Phelan)、阿什利·拉瑞西 (Ashley Laracey)、罗曼·梅希亚 (Roman Mejia)、乔治娜·帕斯科金 (Georgina Pazcoguin)、萨拉·梅恩斯 (Sara Mearns)、丹尼尔·乌布利希 (Daniel Ulbricht) 和纳登 (Nadon) 女士产生了突出的影响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="500" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-777531?width=700&amp;height=500" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Dancers performing &#39;From You Within Me&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Erin Baiano</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>至于 NYCB 活跃剧目中的最新曲目，无论是克里斯托弗·惠尔登 (Christopher Wheeldon) 的《From You Within Me》，还是阿诺德·勋伯格 (Arnold Schoenberg) 有时闪闪发光的《Verklärte Nacht》，阿莉莎·皮雷斯 (Alysa Pires) 的《标准偏差》(Standard Deviation)，由杰克·弗雷尔 (Jack Frerer) 委托创作的断断续续的喧闹配乐，堪称有效的创造性展示。</p><p>画家凯莉·曼宁 (Kylie Manning) 为威尔登先生的 32 分钟、12 名舞者的作品提供了前后幕布，每个幕布都暗示着一望无际的崎岖地形，或者可能是波涛汹涌的大海，让人想起无人居住的星球上荒凉的表面。她的中性紧身衣大多是猩红色的，看起来就像松弛的皮肤。惠尔登先生旋转盘旋的编舞是由一群舞者的起伏演变而来，融入曼宁女士的油漆描边窗帘中，当沐浴在玛丽·路易斯·盖革的昏暗和阴暗的灯光下时，有时会感觉模糊。虽然编舞的舞蹈具有绘画中扫过的颜料笔触的感觉，但动作更多的是大气而不是引人注目。默恩斯女士的出现有很多特色时刻，她的出现更多地归功于她令人印象深刻的身体能力，而不是惠尔登先生的发明。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="500" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-777532?width=700&amp;height=500" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 《标准差》中的 Nadon 女士和她的同伴</p><p class="imageCredit">Photo: Erin Baiano</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Pires 女士的 23 分钟“标准偏差”设置了重复出现的、规则的几何排列，与 Frerer 先生蜿蜒、爵士、萨克斯管为主的配乐形成鲜明对比。她的编舞重点是双手成角度的手臂，当舞者将双手握在背后时，他们看起来像是被戴上了手铐。这部作品由 12 名舞者的裸露手臂构成的独特、四四方方的姿势比两位女主角蒂勒·佩克 (Tiler Peck) 和纳登 (Nadon) 女士裸露双腿的芭蕾舞标准动作更具生动的影响力。达纳·奥斯本 (Dana Osborne) 的浅灰色或蓝色服装将舞蹈的焦点集中在手臂和腿部的动作上，但仅此而已。</p><p>贾斯汀·佩克 (Justin Peck) 的丹·迪肯 (Dan Deacon) 录制的音乐《时代在飞速前进》(The Times Are Racing) 在竞选期间被编排为包括最新作品的账单的结束，它以明显的权威和活力完成了这一任务。 One of his signature sneaker ballets, the challenging work provides NYCB&#39;s dancers with more than enough invention to entertain and engage audiences. With both Mr. Ratmansky and Mr. Peck in place for NYCB&#39;s 75th, their inspiration and direction should sustain the company&#39;s dancers in both the short and long run.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Greskovic writes about dance for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 09 May 2023 21:35:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Dance/Ballet</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>dance</category><category> ballet</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Gilder Center’s Architecture Is an Expression of the Earth]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In its fluid, free-form design, the American Museum of Natural History&#39;s new addition evokes the gentle contours that come from living processes acting over deep time. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10416900472008133444704589584271495422130"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772117?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education, and Innovation</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Iwan Baan </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10416900472008133444704589584271495422130"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> Michael J. Lewis</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated April 29, 2023 7:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>纽约</em></p><p><strong>Is there a museum</strong> anywhere that has not just built an addition? If not, it soon will. Ours is a museum-enlarging age. An architect can build a lucrative practice on that fact (one thinks of Renzo Piano or Annabelle Selldorf ).</p><p> But additions are a tricky business. You tamper with a landmark at your peril, as Michael Graves learned with his radical proposal of the 1980s to absorb the Whitney Museum within a postmodern colossus. It&#39;s much safer to design a neutral box that offers no visual competition. Or to practice museological social distancing, as when Mr. Piano set his 2013 addition to the Kimbell Art Museum away from Louis Kahn&#39;s sublime building.</p><p> It is nonetheless possible to enlarge a museum in a way that is expressive of the present moment, that is poetically evocative of its purpose and content, and that does not stick out like a sore thumb. Such is the lesson of the Richard Gilder Center for Science, Education and Innovation, Studio Gang&#39;s $465 million addition to the American Museum of Natural History in New York, which opens May 4.</p><p> The AMNH is a patchwork of a building, a four-block sprawl along the west side of Central Park and more than a century in the making. It was envisioned as a foursquare citadel in red granite, with round towers at the corners and a burly Romanesque portal at the center of each side. Only the south wing was fully realized, and while monumental entrances were eventually built to the east and north, the west side languished.</p><p> In 2014 Studio Gang was commissioned to design a 230,000-square-foot addition that would provide exhibition and classroom space and also serve as a new entrance pavilion. But it had to do still more. Because the Romanesque master plan had never been completed, many of the passages were dead ends, which the addition was expected to open—with no fewer than 33 connections. A tall order, like expecting the missing piece of a jigsaw puzzle not only to fit but to transform the rest of the puzzle. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772110?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The atrium at the Gilder Center</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Iwan Baan</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The new pavilion is an essay in free-form design, fluidly curved within and without, and is not so much biomorphic as geomorphic. Jeanne Gang, the founder of Studio Gang, told me that she was inspired by the image of “a canyon, worn down by wind, weather and water.” Instead of a literal facsimile of nature, she wanted to evoke it abstractly, through the gentle contours that come from living processes acting over deep time.</p><p> Free-form design can be a breach of architectural good manners, but Ms. Gang&#39;s canyon inspiration works better than expected. It is aligned with the museum&#39;s crucial east-west axis on West 79th Street, which is itself a canyon of tall buildings, and it opens itself to the street grid in a way no other part of the museum does.</p><p> Yet at every step it defers to the older buildings, and not only by matching their height. To either side of the cleft, the facade swells outward in a nod to the Romanesque towers; meanwhile the same pink granite is used as the entrance on Central Park West.</p><p> The interior, a five-story well of light and space, is a rhapsody of flowing structure. Its walls billow and swell, and then abruptly pucker into an opening; it suggests what it would feel like to be inside a Henry Moore sculpture. Its curved surfaces are composed of shotcrete, concrete hosed at high pressure onto a steel rebar cage, forming both the structure and the visible surface. The treatment of the surfaces has been carefully studied to give them a fine-grained handmade texture, one of those subtle tactile refinements that one senses but does not consciously notice. Another is the light, which pours in from the full-height curtain wall of the entrance and from three circular skylights, and which takes on a superb and gentle softness as it reflects off the irregular curves. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-772118?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Gilder Center&#39;s library</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Alvaro Keding/AMNH</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> This ceremonial hall is not the only great space in the Gilder Center. The fourth-story reading room is a cozy tent of a space, its hefty central column carrying a great spread of structural ribs; one might as well be reading under a mighty oak tree, which feels continuous with the canopy outside the oversized window. Ms. Gang worked to make sure all her windows were treated to be visible to flying birds (she spoke movingly of her distress at “the small songbirds whose long journey of migration ends on a sheet of glass”).</p><p> Where necessary, the architecture recedes into invisibility, as in—appropriately enough—“Invisible Worlds,” an immersive and interactive experience that takes place in a 5,800-square-foot oval space. But this is a windowless exception in a building that is otherwise conspicuously, even extravagantly, lavish with sunlight.</p><p> It was not long ago that museums arranged their collections to depict a system of order, either an evolutionary sequence (as with natural history or art) or a structure of interrelationships (as with anthropology). To endorse any sort of systematic order has increasingly come to be seen as arrogantly elitist, and many exhibitions, in the US and elsewhere, have been reconfigured to express a multiplicity of interpretations. The consequence is a distressing sense of uncertainty.</p><p> But there is nothing uncertain about the Gilder Center. Its structure and space celebrate nature, in all its splendor and complexity, and not—miracle of miracles—the architect who designed it.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Lewis teaches architectural history at Williams and reviews architecture for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 29 Apr 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-gilder-centers-architecture-is-an-expression-of-the-earth-93323e2c<category>艺术评论</category><category>Technical Services</category><category> Architects</category><category> Design Services</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>Architecture</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> architecture</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>technical services</category><category> architects</category><category> design services</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category></item></channel></rss>